05017nam a22005175i 9780822388708DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20082008ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223887087 a10.1515/97808223887082doi  a(DE-B1597)553185  a(OCoLC)1112834306  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aN6537.M654bA35 2008 7aART0160002bisacsh1 aMorris, Robert, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHave I Reasons :bWork and Writings, 1993-2007 /cRobert Morris; Nena Tsouti-Schillinger. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2008] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b128 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tIndiana Street (1993) -- tWriting with Davidson: Some Afterthoughts after Doing Blind Time IV: Drawing with Davidson (1993) -- tThe Art of Donald Davidson (1995) -- tSteam (1995) -- tProfessional Rules -- tThinking Back about Him: On the Death of Richard Bellamy (1998) -- tCézanne's Mountains (1998) -- tSize Matters (2000) -- tThreading the Labyrinth (2001) -- tSolecisms of Sight: Specular Speculations (2001) -- tThoughts on Hegel's Owl (2002) -- tMaybe the Angel in Dürer (2003) -- tFrom a Chomskian Couch: The Imperialistic Unconscious (2003) -- tToward an Ophthalmology of the Aesthetic and an Orthopedics of Seeing (2004) -- tNotes on Less than (2004) -- tThe Birthday Boy (2004) -- tJasper Johns: The First Decade (2005) -- tChronology -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRobert Morris, a leading figure in postwar American art, is best known as a pioneer of minimalist sculpture, process art, and earthworks. Yet Morris has resisted affiliation with any one movement or style. An extraordinarily versatile artist, he has produced dances, performance pieces, prints, paintings, drawings, and installations, working with materials including plywood, felt, dirt, aluminum, steel mesh, fiberglass, and encaustic. Throughout his career, Morris has written influential critical essays, commenting on his own work as well as that of other artists, and exploring through text many of the theoretical concerns addressed in his artwork-about perception, materiality, space, and the process of artmaking. Have I Reasons presents seventeen of Morris's essays, six of which have never been published before. Written over the past fifteen years, the essays, along with the volume's many illustrations, provide an invaluable record of the recent thought of a major American artist.The writings are arranged chronologically, beginning with "Indiana Street," a vivid autobiographical account of the artist's early years in Kansas City, Missouri. Have I Reasons includes reflections on Morris's own site-specific installations; transcripts of seminars he conducted in conjunction with exhibitions; and the textual element of The Birthday Boy, the two-screen video-and-sound piece he installed at the Galleria dell'Accademia in Florence, Italy, on the occasion of the five hundredth anniversary of Michelangelo's David. Essays range from original interpretations of Cézanne's Mont Sainte-Victoire paintings and Jasper Johns' early work to engagements with one of Morris's most significant interlocutors, the philosopher Donald Davidson. Have I Reasons conveys not only Morris's enduring deep interest in philosophy and issues of resemblance and representation but also his more recent turn toward directly addressing contemporary social and political issues such as corporate excess and preemptive belligerence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 7aART / Individual Artists / General.2bisacsh1 aTsouti-Schillinger, Nena, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822388708zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822388708423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822388708.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles